        <p>Just as heaven’s order is reflected by images such as  Cartesian designs in the beadloom, the tangle of earth’s living disorder is sometimes given visual representation using random or nonlinear designs.  A labyrinth of unpredictably branching forms can be seen in tunnels below Mayan temples, in stories such as Octavio Paz’ Labyrinth of Solitude, and in visual designs such as South American pottery, tattoos, and  molas. These too sometimes make an appearance in beadwork, although that is more rare than the geometric variety. In the Myan design above, labyrinth-like branching frames random variation of colors. Here the color variation is subtle, but artists can control the range of variation to suit their own tastes or those of their customers, as we see in this Mayan beaded purse:</p>
